data.content:
This is a known .NET platform change. Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## What happened

**DSA was fully removed on macOS in .NET 11.** Apple's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) have never supported DSA. In earlier .NET versions, macOS DSA support was provided via an OpenSSL shim, but:

- **.NET 7** – DSA was marked `[Obsolete]` (`SYSLIB0028`) across all platforms.
- **.NET 9** – The OpenSSL-based DSA backend on macOS was deprecated.
- **.NET 11** – `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.

Windows and Linux still have native OS support (CNG / OpenSSL), so those builds continue to work—for now. DSA is on the removal path everywhere.

## How to fix it

Since you only **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), use **BouncyCastle** for cross-platform DSA verification:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the built-in DSA call:

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(
    byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] message, byte[] signature)
{
    var publicKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory
        .CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);

    var signer = new DsaSigner();
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);

    // Decode the DER-encoded signature into (r, s)
    var derSeq = (Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Sequence)
        Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Object.FromByteArray(signature);
    var r = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[0]).Value;
    var s = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[1]).Value;

    // Hash the message with SHA-1 (typical for legacy DSA)
    var digest = System.Security.Cryptography.SHA1.HashData(message);

    return signer.VerifySignature(digest, r, s);
}
```

## Long-term recommendation

If you control both signing and verification, **migrate to ECDSA or Ed25519**—these are supported natively on all platforms and are not on any deprecation path. Use the BouncyCastle approach above as a bridge to verify existing legacy DSA signatures during the transition.
